Objectives covered in this lecture

  • [O1]: Develop an understanding of soil phase relations, index properties, and their application to soil classification and compaction

After this lecture we will be able to:

  • Calculate the bulk, dry, saturated, and buoyant unit weight of soil.
  • Calculate water content and the degree of saturation.
  • Calculate void ratio and porosity of soils.

Density and unit weight

Ratio of mass (\(m\)) to the volume (\(V\)) it occupies.

\(\rho=m/V\)

Ratio of weight (\(W\)) to the volume (\(V\)) it occupies.

\(\gamma=W/V\)

Ratio of density of solid (\(\rho\)) to the density of water (\(\rho_w\)).

\(G_s=\rho/\rho_w\)
Note: that weight is mass times gravity. Therefore:
\(\gamma=W/V=m g/V= g \rho \)
\(\gamma=g \rho\)

Soil phases

Soils are a collection of particles (solids) and voids. The voids in a soil can be filled with gas or water.
A soil with 0 water content.
A soil with water and gas.
A soil without gas.

Phase diagram

VOLUME

WEIGHT

From the previous slide we can construct our first relationships:
\( W_t=W_s+ W_w \)


Similarly for the total volume:
\( V_t=V_s+V_w+V_a=V_s+V_v \)


With the volume of voids equal to:
\( V_v=V_w+V_a \)
Note: The following applies to phase diagram problems:
  1. If you know volumes and density \(\implies\) you can calculate weights.
  2. If you know weights and density \(\implies\) you can calculate volumes.
  3. If you know volumes and weights \(\implies\) you can calculate densities.

Measuring water content

Three ways of quantifying water in soils:
Ratio of the weight of water to the weight of solids.
\( w[\%]= \frac{W_w}{W_s} \times 100 \)
Is the ratio of the volume of water \(V_w\) to the total volume \(V_t\).

\( \Theta=\frac{V_w}{V_t} \)

Example 2.1

A soil sample is put in a container with mass 12.51 gr. The soil plus the container weighs 54.80 gr (mass is measured). The sample was left in the oven overnight at 105\(^o\)C and weighed 50.51 gr. Calculate: (i) the weight of solids, (ii) the weight of water, and (iii) the water content in %.

Is the ratio of volume of water \(V_w\) to the volume of voids \(V_v\). It is often reported in % and it is between 0% and 100%.
\( S[\%]= \frac{V_w}{V_v} \times 100 \)

Quiz 2.1

What is the saturation of a fully saturated soil?
  1. 25%
  2. 0%
  3. 100%
  4. 50%

Measures of void

The most common measures of space in soils are the void ratio and the porosity.

Ratio of volume of voids \(V_v\) to the volume of solids \(V_s\).

\( e=V_v/V_s \)

Ratio of volume of voids \(V_v\) to the total volume \(V_t\).

\( n= V_v/V_t \)

Example 2.2

Show that \(n=e/(1+e)\).

Start with definition of porosity

\(n=\frac{V_v}{V_t}\)

Invert the equation:

\(1/n=\frac{V_t}{V_v}= \cfrac{V_s+V_v}{V_v}=1/e + 1\)

Re-invert the equation

\(n=\frac{e}{1+e}\)

Unit weight of soils

Is the ratio of the total weight \(W_t\), over the total volume of the soil \(V_t\).
\( \gamma_t=W_t/V_t \)
Is the ratio of the weight of solids \(W_s\), over the total volume of the soil \(V_t\).
\( \gamma_d=W_s/V_t \)
Is the unit weight of soil when \(S=100\%\) or \(V_v=V_w\).
\( \gamma_{sat}= W_{sat}/V_t \)
Is also known as the submerged unit weight or the effective unit weight.
\( \gamma'=\gamma_{sat}-\gamma_w \)

Example 2.3

Unit weight is the connector between the weights and the volumes. Using phase diagrams find an expression for the total unit weight \(\gamma_t\) and show that \(S e= w G_s\).

Useful relationships

For unit weight:

\(\gamma_t=\cfrac{\gamma_w (G_s+S e)}{1+e} \)

\(\gamma_d=\cfrac{\gamma_w G_s}{1+e} \)

\(\gamma_{sat}=\cfrac{\gamma_w (G_s+ e)}{1+e} \)

\( \gamma_t=\gamma_d (1+w/100)\)

Relationship between saturation, void ratio, specific gravity, and water content:

\( S e= w G_s \)
To remember: structural engineers are wacky guys

Example 2.4

A sample of fully saturated clay with \( G_s=2.66 \) weighs 1350 g in its natural state and 975 g after drying. Solve:

  1. The natural water content.
  2. Void ratio and porosity.
  3. Total or wet unit weight.
  4. Dry unit weight.

Example 2.5

A cylinder contains 500 cm3 of loose dry sand which weighs 750 g, and under static load of 200 kPa the volume is reduced 1%, and then by vibration it is reduced 10% of the original volume. Assume the specific gravity of the sand is \(G_s=2.65\). Compute the void ratio, porosity, dry unit weight, and total unit weight corresponding to each of the following cases:

  1. Loose sand.
  2. Under static load.
  3. Vibrated and loaded sand.
